00:41:08.380 --> 00:41:12.369
differences where we might need to look in the future to see if there

699
00:41:12.400 --> 00:41:15.550
are any more subtle differences between the CD8 T cells that

700
00:41:15.620 --> 00:41:16.580
arise

701
00:41:17.380 --> 00:41:21.100
when they're primed by a DC1 or abnormally primed by a

702
00:41:21.160 --> 00:41:23.919
DC2? And that's in this experiment. This is the last experiment.

703
00:41:24.580 --> 00:41:25.520
So CD8 T cells,

704
00:41:27.240 --> 00:41:31.140
we have these mice. This mouse only has DC2s, and

705
00:41:31.180 --> 00:41:33.040
this mouse only has DC1s.

706
00:41:33.880 --> 00:41:35.360
And here's a wild type for a control.

707
00:41:35.440 --> 00:41:39.100
And then we immunize with a dead

708
00:41:39.440 --> 00:41:43.140
macro vaccine as a control. And so what we're doing here is we

709
00:41:43.320 --> 00:41:47.160
immunize once, we immunize at day seven, and we're harvesting all

710
00:41:47.220 --> 00:41:49.720
tetramer positive cells at day 11.

711
00:41:50.020 --> 00:41:52.840
So four days after the second immunization.

712
00:41:52.890 --> 00:41:56.420
And we took these cells, and we did, in collaboration with

713
00:41:58.360 --> 00:42:01.600
Naresh Saligrama and his postdoc, Chandri Thakur,

714
00:42:03.160 --> 00:42:05.380
we did a big single-cell RNA seq analysis.

715
00:42:06.080 --> 00:42:06.240
And

716
00:42:07.340 --> 00:42:11.220
generally, if you lump them all together, we see naive and memory populations

717
00:42:11.340 --> 00:42:15.240
which migrate to a stem-like, some people would call it

